hall, there was an attempt to
suppress the evidence about

23:07.586 --> 23:10.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this particular killing.

23:10.356 --> 23:12.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can the Justice Department
investigate that as well? Will
you investigate that?

23:12.791 --> 23:16.428 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
VANITA GUPTA: So, that is a
separate criminal matter.

23:16.428 --> 23:20.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, obviously, the criminal
investigators will be looking at
all the available evidence

23:20.399 --> 23:25.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pertaining to that particular
matter. But the work that -- the
investigation that we

23:25.271 --> 23:29.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
announced today is a civil
pattern and practice
investigation. And that is
really aimed at

23:29.908 --> 23:34.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
looking at whether there is a
pattern and practice of
constitutional violations being

23:34.747 --> 23:39.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
committed by the Chicago Police
Department in the areas of use
of force and accountability.

23:39.852 --> 23:43.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will, obviously, consider a
particular individual incident
as we look at whether

23:43.922 --> 23:48.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's a pattern or practice,
but this is separate from
criminal investigations.

23:48.360 --> 23:51.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, let's say
you do find a pattern or a
practice. What happens then?

23:51.563 --> 23:54.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How do you try to
stamp that out?

23:54.400 --> 23:58.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VANITA GUPTA: Yes, so after --
if we do find that upon kind of
a thorough review, we will

23:58.871 --> 24:02.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
then issue our findings
publicly. It's something that we
think is important for the
American

24:02.775 --> 24:05.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
public to be -- to understand
and be aware of kind of what we
have looked at and what

24:05.544 --> 24:08.013 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we found.

24:08.013 --> 24:13.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then we would seek to
negotiate through a
collaborative negotiation an
agreement with

24:13.052 --> 24:17.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the city to remedy the problems
that we found. And in the vast
majority of jurisdictions

24:17.756 --> 24:22.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where the Justice Department
goes in, we are able to achieve
a negotiated settlement that

24:22.961 --> 24:26.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then will be court-enforceable
with a monitor, and that seeks
to remedy all the constitutional

24:26.865 --> 24:29.735 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
violations that we found.

24:29.735 --> 24:33.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Our colleagues
at "Frontline" and The
Washington Post did an
investigation,

24:33.872 --> 24:37.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or really an examination, of a
lot of prior instances where the
Justice Department tried

24:37.943 --> 24:43.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to fix problems within police
departments around the country,
and the results were mixed.

24:43.082 --> 24:48.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They found examples of use of
force going up in some
departments after the
settlements.

24:48.454 --> 24:52.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Morale plummeted in others.
Community relations in many were
still deeply troubled.

24:52.091 --> 24:55.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Why do you think Chicago
will be different?

24:55.961 --> 25:00.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VANITA GUPTA: So, just for
something that I think is
important to understand about
our

25:00.099 --> 25:03.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
investigations, is, when we
actually achieve an agreement to
remedy these problems, we

25:03.936 --> 25:07.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
will often, in those
jurisdictions, see spikes in
reporting because there actually
is data

25:07.005 --> 25:08.340 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
collection, there's tracking.

25:08.340 --> 25:09.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Because people
are just paying more attention.

25:09.875 --> 25:11.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VANITA GUPTA: They're paying
more attention. They have more
confidence in the actual systems

25:11.510 --> 25:13.746 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that we have put in place.

25:13.746 --> 25:18.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so that is actually quite
typical of our investigations.
We have also been recently

25:18.784 --> 25:23.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in places like East Haven,
Connecticut, and Seattle,
Washington, where they have
really

25:23.021 --> 25:27.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
transformed the way that they
are engaged in using force, when
they are using force,

25:27.526 --> 25:30.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what kind of accountability
systems they have in place.

25:30.963 --> 25:36.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is resulting in very
significant reductions in the
uses of force, while keeping
crime

25:36.001 --> 25:40.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and violent crime down. And I
think that that's really
important. In places like East
Haven,

25:40.305 --> 25:43.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we have been able to document
transformed relationships
between the community and law

25:43.041 --> 25:45.544 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
enforcement.

25:45.544 --> 25:50.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so these are -- you know,
look, policing is a very complex
-- it's a set of complex

25:50.115 --> 25:55.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issues. And I think that we have
been working very
collaboratively along the
process with

25:55.888 --> 26:00.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
law enforcement, with community,
listening to them directly about
what they're experiencing

26:00.592 --> 26:03.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
every day in order to come out
with the best kind of police
department that the community

26:03.796 --> 26:06.365 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
deserves in these jurisdictions.

26:06.365 --> 26:11.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The head of
the FBI, James Comey, has said
that all of these criticisms

26:11.470 --> 26:15.441 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of police, all of these
investigations may in some way
be causing police to step back

26:15.441 --> 26:18.177 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and not doing their
job as effectively.

26:18.177 --> 26:22.514 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you think that that's true?
And, if so, do you worry that
yet another investigation

26:22.514 --> 26:26.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
could suppress the work that
police are trying to do, because
they're scared?

26:26.118 --> 26:28.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VANITA GUPTA: Well, so Director
Comey actually said that Justice
Department scrutiny is critical

26:28.720 --> 26:31.523 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to the field of policing.

26:31.523 --> 26:35.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what he did say -- and
there's obviously a robust
discussion right now about these

26:35.027 --> 26:40.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
issues around whether there is
de-policing or not. And I think
the reality is, there

26:40.098 --> 26:45.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is no data to back up the
assertions. We know that law
enforcement every day, police
officers

26:45.204 --> 26:48.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
every day are continuing to do
what they do every day, which is
to put themselves in danger

26:48.440 --> 26:50.976 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to protect the rest of us.

26:50.976 --> 26:56.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, obviously, though, we are
interested in accumulating and
collecting data. But,

26:56.782 --> 26:59.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for now, there is nothing to
contradict what police officers,
what we're hearing police

26:59.151 --> 27:01.787 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
officers say around the country.

27:01.787 --> 27:04.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The attorney
general in her announcement
today said she hoped that

27:04.456 --> 27:07.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this investigation would also
serve as a deterrent to other
police forces.

27:07.559 --> 27:10.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is there any evidence that
that actually happens?

27:10.062 --> 27:13.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VANITA GUPTA: Well, I have spent
a lot of the last year speaking
directly with law enforcement,

27:13.365 --> 27:16.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with police agencies
and the like.

27:16.001 --> 27:19.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what they are doing right
now is, I think, quite laudable.
They're looking at our consent

27:19.972 --> 27:25.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
decrees. They're examining the
president's report on 21st
century policing. They are

27:25.010 --> 27:30.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trying to take proactive steps
to ensure that, if there is a
critical incident, that it
doesn't

27:30.883 --> 27:34.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
create mass civil unrest and
that they are preempting,
through training, through
policies,

27:34.786 --> 27:40.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
through changes that they are
voluntarily undertaking, so that
they can have constitutional

27:40.359 --> 27:43.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
policing, while keeping the
public safe and, frankly, not
have a pattern and practice
investigation

27:43.996 --> 27:46.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
if that can be held off.

27:46.665 --> 27:49.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so I actually think there is
a very robust conversation
happening right now around the

27:49.768 --> 27:53.572 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
country among law enforcement on
a whole range of these issues.

27:53.572 --> 27:56.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
acting Assistant Attorney
General Vanita Gupta, thank you
very

27:56.842 --> 27:58.644 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

27:58.644 --> 28:04.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
VANITA GUPTA: Thank you.

28:04.616 --> 28:09.555 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Stay with us.

