president's speech last night.

31:48.573 --> 31:52.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The interesting thing is that
there was unanimity on the part
of all these Republicans, the

31:52.177 --> 31:54.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ones who spoke, and some of the
Democrats, that the president
didn't quite do enough

31:54.546 --> 31:54.880 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
last night.

31:54.880 --> 31:56.548 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: Right.

31:56.548 --> 31:59.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, here's what Republicans
wanted. They wanted two things.
They wanted the president

31:59.484 --> 32:04.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to say that we're at war with
radical Islam and they wanted to
hear him say we have a

32:04.022 --> 32:07.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
different strategy. And they
didn't get either one of those
things. And they got a lecture

32:07.459 --> 32:10.095 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on gun control from the
president, which they also hate.

32:10.095 --> 32:16.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it was pretty easy for them
to say that they disagreed with
it. What wasn't easy was

32:16.134 --> 32:21.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to see just where Republicans go
next. Each of them has sort of
different avenue in terms

32:21.807 --> 32:25.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of what they'd do to
handle ISIS and terrorism.

32:25.877 --> 32:29.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, if you're Ted
Cruz, you want the president and
several of the others to

32:29.948 --> 32:36.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say the words radical Islamic
terrorism, those words, no other
way of putting it. And if

32:36.288 --> 32:39.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're Marco Rubio, you want to
say the president's weak. That
seems to be the theme that we
see

32:39.491 --> 32:41.226 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
emerging.

32:41.226 --> 32:46.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: I think that's a
pretty consistent theme that has
been coming from Republican

32:46.298 --> 32:50.735 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
presidential candidates,
Republicans on Capitol Hill,
that President Obama is not
using strong

32:50.735 --> 32:54.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
