laws. Are they working to reduce
emissions or increase recycling,

44:06.210 --> 44:08.379 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for instance?

44:08.379 --> 44:12.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MA JUN (through translator):
Scores have been on the rise.
And the score for Apple has
exceeded

44:12.817 --> 44:15.119 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
70 twice.

44:15.119 --> 44:20.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Apple ranks
number one, ironic, since the
company initially declined

44:20.424 --> 44:26.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to work with IPE. It relented
after IPE's investigations
linked several polluting
factories

44:26.931 --> 44:31.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the Silicon Valley giant.
Today, Apple and several global
brands use the group's

44:31.002 --> 44:33.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
data as a resource.

44:33.204 --> 44:36.240 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
Here's retailer
Target's Ninh Trinh.

44:36.240 --> 44:41.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NINH TRINH, Target: We look at
IPE to ensure that there are no
irregularities. What is

44:41.779 --> 44:47.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the progress of our suppliers
that have irregularities that
need to be reported?

44:47.919 --> 44:52.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Several,
like Macy's, J.C. Penney, and
Victoria's Secret, were rated

44:52.924 --> 44:58.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at zero. The brands insist they
monitor their suppliers. Macy's
and Penney told us they

44:58.095 --> 45:07.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
never heard from IPE. The group
says each brand was contacted by
letter. Ma says IPE

45:07.838 --> 45:12.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will add brands on the next
version of its mobile app, not
just the factory names that

45:12.276 --> 45:15.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mean little to consumers,
especially in the West.

45:15.980 --> 45:22.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDA GREER: China's pollution
problem is caused by about
one-third by export to America

45:22.086 --> 45:26.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and to Western Europe. So this
pollution is our pollution, and
I think we have an ethical

45:26.290 --> 45:30.127 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
obligation to help reduce it.

45:30.127 --> 45:34.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And even as
China begins cleaning up, she
and Ma Jun fear the global

45:34.699 --> 45:40.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
supply chain will migrate to
less expensive countries, eager,
as China was a generation

45:40.004 --> 45:45.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ago, to attract new factories,
but lacking systems to safeguard
the environment.

45:45.576 --> 45:50.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," this is
Fred de Sam Lazaro in Tianjin,
China.

45:50.181 --> 45:55.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Fred's report was
funded in part by the Pulitzer
Center on Crisis Reporting.

45:55.219 --> 46:07.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A version of this story also
appeared on the PBS show
"Religion &amp; Ethics Newsweekly."

46:07.531 --> 46:11.335 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
art

46:11.335 --> 46:18.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Finally tonight, one
of North America's biggest
contemporary art fairs wrapped

46:18.743 --> 46:22.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Miami this weekend.

46:22.046 --> 46:25.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Jared
Bowen was there to see how the
annual gathering is changing

46:25.650 --> 46:28.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the city's identity.

46:28.986 --> 46:34.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: For a week every
December, Miami becomes the
center of the contemporary art

46:34.525 --> 46:41.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
world. Art Basel, now in its
14th year, is an international
gathering of more than 260

46:41.232 --> 46:46.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
galleries, 4,000 artists, many
big-name dealers and collectors,
and an estimated 70,000 art

46:46.771 --> 46:50.074 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
aficionados from
all walks of life.

46:50.074 --> 46:51.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NOAH HOROWITZ, Director, Art
Basel Americas: Fairs have
become a real central meeting
point

46:51.509 --> 46:53.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for a lot of those
different constituents.

46:53.744 --> 46:57.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: Noah Horowitz is
director of Art Basel Americas.

46:57.515 --> 47:01.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NOAH HOROWITZ: These are the
leading galleries anyway really.
And they're coming here to

47:01.919 --> 47:06.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
show some of their best work.
So, collectors come really
because of the quality of the

47:06.057 --> 47:08.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
galleries and the quality of
artists on view. You don't get
this anywhere. And for us, that

47:08.192 --> 47:10.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is what makes it so special.

47:10.461 --> 47:14.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: Think of all the
works you see in museums around
the world. They're here,

47:14.932 --> 47:22.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but for sale, from Picasso
masterpieces to a towering tree
by Chinese sensation Ai Weiwei.

47:22.173 --> 47:26.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's supposedly $3 billion
worth of art on display this
year, and the show has spread

47:26.977 --> 47:33.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
across Miami to some two dozens
satellite fairs showcasing works
by artists from around

47:33.984 --> 47:36.220 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the globe.

47:36.220 --> 47:39.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chilean sculptor Ivan Navarro
says he has seen an enormous
shift for Latin American

47:39.724 --> 47:42.493 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
artists in just the past decade.

47:42.493 --> 47:47.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
IVAN NAVARRO, Artist: When I
started showing here in 2005, it
was just the beginning of

47:47.998 --> 47:55.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Latino-American art being
available to the wide market.
And now it's absolutely an art

47:55.573 --> 48:00.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is recognized as important
as American art, as European
art. It's just part of the

48:00.077 --> 48:03.214 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
universal art history.

48:03.214 --> 48:07.551 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JARED BOWEN: Navarro is
represented here by Maria Baro
and her gallery based in Sao
Paulo,

48:07.551 --> 48:07.985 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Brazil.

48:07.985 --> 48:10.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why are you here?

48:10.254 --> 48:18.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIA BARO, Baro Gallery: I'm
here because I want to sell. I
do to do sold out.

48:18.629 --> 48:23.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: Frances Trombly is
a Miami native, this year
displaying work at a satellite
fair

48:23.901 --> 48:26.303 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
called Pulse.

48:26.303 --> 48:29.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEYDEN RODRIGUEZ-CASANOVA,
Dimensions Variable: What we try
to do every December is
concentrate

48:29.607 --> 48:32.276 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on the artists that
are working in Miami.

48:32.276 --> 48:36.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: She and her artist
husband, Leyden
Rodriguez-Casanova, are also
co-directors

48:36.914 --> 48:42.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of an independent gallery in
downtown Miami called Dimensions
Variable. They say they

48:42.019 --> 48:45.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have seen a sea change in
Miami's art scene since Art
Basel.

48:45.589 --> 48:48.993 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEYDEN RODRIGUEZ-CASANOVA:
Because of the fair coming here,
because of this new awareness

48:48.993 --> 48:54.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of what is going on here,
there's a lot of people coming
to visit here, whether it's

48:54.098 --> 48:59.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
curators, collectors, that are
kind of looking to Miami and
looking into what's happening

48:59.403 --> 49:03.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the city. And the artists
that are working here are being
able to take advantage of those

49:03.240 --> 49:05.309 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
possibilities.

49:05.309 --> 49:10.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: One of the most
visible signs of change since
Art Basel came to Miami is

49:10.214 --> 49:15.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the graffiti-clad neighborhood
of Wynwood, a warehouse district
once avoided by locals.

49:15.820 --> 49:20.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's now a magnet for gallery,
studios and perhaps most of all
developers.

49:20.391 --> 49:26.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CRAIG ROBINS, Developer: I build
neighborhoods. And to give
neighborhoods a sense of place,

49:26.630 --> 49:31.635 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I feel that art, design,
architecture are all important
components that can make a
neighborhood

49:31.635 --> 49:34.104 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
really feel special
and different.

49:34.104 --> 49:38.209 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JARED BOWEN: Collector,
philanthropist and developer
Craig Robins stands at the nexus

49:38.209 --> 49:44.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of art and commerce in Miami.
After helping redevelop South
Beach, in the '90s, Robins

49:44.882 --> 49:49.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
started work on a desolate site
in Midtown, leveling abandoned
buildings to produce a

49:49.587 --> 49:54.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mix of high-end fashion and
furniture stores, all surrounded
by giant works of art and
renamed

49:54.625 --> 49:56.493 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Design District.

49:56.493 --> 50:00.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He also helped bring
Art Basel to Miami.

50:00.231 --> 50:06.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CRAIG ROBINS: Miami has become a
city where we define ourselves
with culture. And you

50:06.637 --> 50:13.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see many different examples of
that. Art Basel was clearly a
catalyst. There are incredible

50:13.277 --> 50:16.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
art collections in the city, and
there are lots of museums that
exist or are merging

50:16.714 --> 50:19.149 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on a new level.

50:19.149 --> 50:23.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: Two of those
museums are the Institute of
Contemporary Art set to open

50:23.320 --> 50:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in a new building in the Design
District in 2017, and the Perez
Art Museum Miami, which

50:29.894 --> 50:33.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
moved into a brand-new $200
million building in 2013.

50:33.931 --> 50:37.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANKLIN SIRMANS, Perez Art
Museum Miami: October 15 was my
first day.

50:37.668 --> 50:40.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: Franklin Sirmans,
who only just recently arrived
from the Los Angeles County

50:40.938 --> 50:44.642 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Museum of Art, is the
Perez Museum's director.

50:44.642 --> 50:51.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANKLIN SIRMANS: In a city like
Miami, our past is short. If
you're going to the museum

50:51.248 --> 50:58.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of modern art, you have to work
through Picasso. There is no way
that you can deny that presence,

50:58.022 --> 51:01.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
whereas, here, it's a
little bit shorter history.

51:01.825 --> 51:06.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: His task at the
Perez, take it from a place with
the base of community support

51:06.964 --> 51:14.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a shiny new building and
find the money to turn it into a
world-class institution.

51:14.038 --> 51:18.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another newcomer is Alexandre
Arrechea, a Cuban sculptor who
this week created a
participatory

51:18.375 --> 51:22.446 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
piece at the Cisneros Fontanals
Art Foundation downtown.

51:22.446 --> 51:27.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALEXANDRE ARRECHEA, Sculptor:
You have to remember places like
New York at some point

51:27.117 --> 51:33.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are very expensive to afford for
many artists, especially coming
from South America, and

51:33.524 --> 51:39.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Miami suddenly becomes a good
opportunity, a place that you
still can afford places for

51:39.430 --> 51:45.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
studios and to create business.
There is obviously a big
competition here, but I think
there's

51:45.302 --> 51:47.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a lot of opportunities here.

51:47.705 --> 51:50.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BOWEN: Opportunities, yes.
The fair brings in millions of
dollars each year to

51:50.474 --> 51:53.410 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the local economy.

51:53.410 --> 51:59.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But some complain that amid all
the hype of Art Basel, the vast
sums of money being spent,

51:59.383 --> 52:03.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all the VIP events, the focus is
too much on big-name outsiders
and not enough on the

52:03.087 --> 52:05.556 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
local scene.

52:05.556 --> 52:11.161 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We run the space because we feel
like the city and the community
and the people here

52:11.161 --> 52:15.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have things to say, really
important things to say. And we
want to foster that.

52:15.866 --> 52:18.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEYDEN RODRIGUEZ-CASANOVA: And
what ends up happening
sometimes, I think, with like
the

52:18.702 --> 52:22.172 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fairs is that you have got a
circuit of fairs, where people
travel the world. And they're

52:22.172 --> 52:25.609 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
basically looking at the same
artist in every single city they
go to.

52:25.609 --> 52:29.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JARED BOWEN: Part of the
challenge is to translate the
energy and excitement Art Basel
generates

52:29.646 --> 52:33.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the rest of the year here
in Miami and to define what it
means to be a great art

52:33.384 --> 52:36.520 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
city in the 21st century.

52:36.520 --> 52:42.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
From Miami, I'm Jared Bowen
for the "PBS NewsHour."

52:42.393 --> 52:45.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can see more of Jared's
coverage of the arts, which he
does for our Boston station,

52:45.662 --> 52:55.572 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on their Web site, WGBH.org.

52:55.572 --> 53:07.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: On the "NewsHour"
online: Nearly three million
Syrian children are out of
school,

53:07.418 --> 53:10.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
displaced from their
homes and communities.

53:10.621 --> 53:15.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But one Syrian artist wants to
encourage young refugees to
return to the classroom, by
making

53:15.626 --> 53:21.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them cheerful places with
bright, colorful murals some of
the students even help paint.

53:21.131 --> 53:27.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can find a photo gallery of
that work on our home page,
PBS.org/NewsHour.

53:27.304 --> 53:32.176 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Tune in later tonight on
"Charlie Rose": George Osborne,
British chancellor of the
exchequer,

53:32.176 --> 53:36.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the U.K.'s new role in
the fight against ISIS.

53:36.547 --> 53:39.416 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the "NewsHour" for
tonight. I'm Gwen Ifill.

53:39.416 --> 53:43.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Join us online and again here
tomorrow evening. For all of us
here at the "PBS NewsHour,"

53:43.153 --> 53:43.520 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
thank you, and good night.
